<h2 class="header"><i>26</i>thermohaline circulation (probably on exam)<a class="headerlink" href="#thermohaline-circulation-probably-on-exam" name="thermohaline-circulation-probably-on-exam">&para;</a></h2>
<ul>
<li>major movements of energy from tropics to poles</li>
<li>some other stuff</li>
</ul>
<h2 class="header"><i>27</i>el nino (classic example)<a class="headerlink" href="#el-nino-classic-example" name="el-nino-classic-example">&para;</a></h2>
<ul>
<li>between 3 and 7 years, it happens</li>
<li>heating and cooling</li>
<li>when it occurs: southeast trade winds revere or weaken, cold upwelling reduced or absent, high pressure over austrilia, rain over south america</li>
<li>changes weather patterns across the world</li>
<li>also, La Nina, like El Nino, but less strong</li>
<li>about  a redistribution of global climate, but not a signal.</li>
</ul>
<h2 class="header"><i>28</i>galapagos islands<a class="headerlink" href="#galapagos-islands" name="galapagos-islands">&para;</a></h2>
<ul>
<li>dry and wet seasons</li>
<li>warm water is nutrient poor, wreaks havoc on marine ecosystems</li>
</ul>
